            <TextArea editable="false" prefHeight="313.0" prefWidth="558.0" text="Decimal Binary and Hexadecimal∶&#10;&#9;Rules of playing binary and hexadecimal are quite same only one change in hexadecimals is that the if number to be Found is greater than 9, then it will be displayed in it’s hexadecimal equivalent i.e.&#10;10 -&gt; A&#9;&#10;11 -&gt; B&#9;&#10;12 -&gt; C&#9;&#10;13 -&gt; D&#9;&#10;14 -&gt; E&#9;&#10;15 -&gt; F&#10;&#10;User Control -&gt;&#10; Click on the button to switch your input 0 to 1 and 1 to 0 as needed.&#10;&#10;Weights in the rows are given as follows&#10;&#10;4X4 -&gt; 8-4-2-1 along the Row.&#9;&#9;&#9; &#10;6X6 -&gt; 32-16-8-4-2-1 along the Row &#10;&#10;THE LEFT—MOST BOX REPRESENTS THE MOST SIGNIFICANT BIT, WHILE THE RIGHT—MOST BOX IS THE LEAST SIGNIFICANT BIT. &#10;FOR EXAMPLE, IF WE HAVE TO FIND BINARY EQUVIALENT OF DECIMAL NUMBER 13 IN 4 X 4 BOARDS, THOSE SOME BITS SHOULD LOOK LIKE THIS: &#10;&#9;&#9;1&#9;1&#9;0&#9;1&#9;=&#9;13&#10;&#10;WEIGHTS  in the rows are given as follows&#10;&#10;THE TOP-MOST BOX IS THE MOST SIGNIFICANT BIT, WHILE THE BOTTOM-MOST BOX IS THE LEAST SIGNIFICANT BIT. &#10;4X4 -&gt; 8-4-2-1 DOWN THE COLUMN.&#9;&#9;6X6 -&gt; 32-16-8-4-2-1 DOWN THE COLUMN.&#10;FOR EXAMPLE, IF WE FOUND 13 UNDER A COLUMN OF BITS IN 4 X 4 BOARD, THE BITS SHOULD BE TOGGLED AS SHOWN IN SIDE FIGURE: &#10;&#9;1&#10;&#9;&#10;&#9;1&#10;&#9;&#10;&#9;0&#10;&#10;&#9;1&#10;&#10;&#9;=&#10;&#10;&#9;13&#10;&#10;EXPLINATION of example∶&#10;THE DECIMAL VALUES OF EACH BIT ARE 8-4-2-1(8 IS THE MOST SIGNIFICANT BIT, WHILE 1 IS THE LEAST SIGNIFICANT) AND 13 IS EQUAL TO 8+4+1, SO WE TOGGLE THE BITS THAT THE BOXES IN ROWS OR COLOUMS CONTAINS NUMBER THE BINARY NUMBER 1101.&#10;&#10;&#10;Decimal to Octal∶&#10;There is only one board size for octal conversion that is 4X4.&#10;&#10;User Control -&gt; &#10;Click on the button to increment the already present number by 1 as needed. When the number becomes 7, then it is again set to 0.&#10;&#10;Weights in the rows are given as follows&#10;&#10;4X4 -&gt; 3584 - 448 – 56 - 1 along the Row.&#10;&#9;&#9;&#9; &#10;THE LEFT—MOST BOX REPRESENTS THE MOST SIGNIFICANT BIT, WHILE THE RIGHT—MOST BOX IS THE LEAST SIGNIFICANT BIT. &#10;FOR EXAMPLE, IF WE HAVE TO FIND OCTAL EQUVIALENT OF DECIMAL NUMBER 1300 IN 4 X 4 BOARDS, THOSE SOME BITS SHOULD LOOK LIKE THIS: &#10;&#9;2&#9;4&#9;2&#9;4&#9;=&#9;1300&#10;&#10;WEIGHTS  in the rows are given as follows:&#10;&#10;THE TOP-MOST BOX IS THE MOST SIGNIFICANT BIT, WHILE THE BOTTOM-MOST BOX IS THE LEAST SIGNIFICANT BIT.&#10;4X4 -&gt; 3584 - 448 – 56 – 1 DOWN THE COLUMN&#10;FOR EXAMPLE, IF WE FOUND 1300 UNDER A COLUMN OF BITS IN 4 X 4 BOARD, THE BITS SHOULD BE TOGGLED AS SHOWN IN SIDE FIGURE:&#10;&#10;&#9;2&#10;&#10;&#9;4&#10;&#9;&#10;&#9;2&#10;&#10;&#9;4&#10;&#10;&#9;=&#10;&#10;&#9;1300&#10;&#10;EXPLINATION of example∶&#10;THE DECIMAL VALUES OF EACH BIT ARE 3584 - 448 – 56 – 1 (3584 IS THE MOST SIGNIFICANT BIT, WHILE 1 IS THE LEAST SIGNIFICANT) AND 1300 IS EQUAL TO 1024+256+16+1, SO WE TOGGLE THE BITS SO THAT THE BOXES IN ROWS OR COLOUMS CONTAINS NUMBER 2424.&#10;&#10;" wrapText="true">
